{{/* WHY: verdict semantics mirrors task_verifier.tmpl's dominance framing
     almost verbatim; REPAIRABLE explicitly names the D-04 one-shot re-plan
     bound so the model never assumes unlimited retries at this level. */ -}}
Verdict semantics — pick exactly one:
  - APPROVED: the gate command exited 0 (when one is declared) and you found
    no blocker-severity deviation across the four dimensions. The authored
    plan is accepted for execution.
  - REPAIRABLE: the plan falls short, but ONE fresh re-plan attempt could
    plausibly fix it — a failing gate with a correctable cause, a
    misaligned or missing child, a dependency or file-touch mistake. This
    verdict sends the plan back for exactly one findings-seeded re-plan
    (D-04) — there is no second re-plan after that one, so the findings you
    report must be the complete, actionable set.
  - BLOCKED: retrying cannot help — the declared contract is unverifiable or
    self-contradictory, the environment itself is broken, or the plan is
    unsafe to accept. This verdict escalates to a human.
A non-zero gate exit means the plan can never be APPROVED — but it does NOT
by itself mean BLOCKED. On a red gate, judge whether one fresh re-plan
attempt could plausibly turn it green: yes → REPAIRABLE, no → BLOCKED. The
orchestrator has already captured the gate's exit code out-of-band and
structurally enforces that dominance regardless of what you write.

{{/* WHY (EVAL-04, coverage-not-conservatism): kept verbatim from
     task_verifier.tmpl — the finding set is the load-bearing artifact this
     template exists to produce. */ -}}
Report a finding for EVERY deviation you observe, however small, tagged with
an explicit severity (e.g. blocker, major, advisory) and an explicit
confidence (e.g. high, medium, low) on each one. Coverage is your job, not
triage — record the full finding set and let severity/confidence speak for
each entry. Config-driven gate policy, not you, decides which findings
actually block; a finding you never reported is a finding that policy can
never act on, so completeness here is the whole point.

